<emphasis box="[348,472,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">B. balaena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from dung traps set in mossy elfin forests at high elevations in the Andes of 
<collectingCountry box="[263,356,799,824]" name="Ecuador" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[415,501,799,824]" name="Bolivia" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
. The closely related but more widespread Andean species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yau &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2018" box="[1171,1271,801,824]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Bromeloecia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ponsa">
<emphasis box="[1171,1271,801,824]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">B. ponsa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also occurs at relatively high elevations.
</paragraph>
